<p>I want to send multiple parameters through a URL with Django. Typically I could do something like below:</p>  <pre><code> url(r'^example/(?P&lt;param1&gt;[\w|\W]+)/(?P&lt;param2&gt;[\w|\W]+)/(?P&lt;param3&gt;[\w|\W]+)/$', views.example, name='example') </code></pre>  <p>The problem is that my 3 parameters can include any characters including "/", so if param1 is say a URL itself, then it will mess up the other parameters for if the following paramters are passed:</p>  <p>param1 = "<a href="http://cnn.com" rel="nofollow">http://cnn.com</a>", param2 = "red", and param3 = "22"</p>  <p>Django will interpret param2 as beginning after the 2nd dash in <a href="http://cnn.com" rel="nofollow">http://cnn.com</a>. Any idea what the best way to resolve this is?</p>  <p>Thank You!</p>